text:
Â°â€¢Â° List of sexist remarks I have encountered in the past month:

1. "Women's identity is from her husband. I don't do house chores because this is Pakistan not Europe." (Coming that from a guy who is raised by a single mother says a lot about how internalized this concept is within the minds of Pakistani people with or without men setting such precedents.) 2. "I hate it when women play the card of 'don't tell me what to do' because, if you don't obey me, I am obviously going to get angry and scold you." 3. "Men should 'sacrifice' their right to dowry so that the show off culture in the society diminishes, the culture whose leaders are women." 4. "Atleast, I don't have to put tons of makeup to look pretty." 5. "My brother is additional secretary who has a higher status than your father and he still likes that his wife cooks him food. That is what our religious, social and cultural values are." 6. "Feminist hou per limits main reh kar. Aurat march type na bano." All this is besides the general disparaging comments that I received from them on my looks during a very normal discussion from these unrelatedly related men. Why is it so hard for men to accept that sometimes there is no right and wrong and just a difference of opinion? They can stoop to any level in order to boast their little egos. All for what? I tell you. The shortcomings in their broughtup and their lack of understanding on how to handle a different pov without being derogatory about it.

Call me rebellious or insolent, but I have found the malady in all this. Guess what, it is not feminism or having a voice to convey my stance. It is your rigidity and ugly inneundo.Rest you can figure on your own what triggers you. (Hint: one of the two small things you possess.) I can stoop to their level too but my arguments are NEVER based on personal remarks about uncontrollable factors unless attacked or provoked otherwise. I will continue to hit men where it hurts them the most. I am not a man hater but I am unapologetically vocal about the fact that I don't respect such species. Never have. Never will. 
Rant over!

P.S I am so proud of people who are breaking the cycle induced with cultural mayhem.

Recently i did a Q/A and someone asked me that why do i always look so angry and serious. He said that "larkiyon ko har waqt smile karni chahiye". I wanted to answer that but putting up a story about it wasn't going to cover it all.
.
So here it goes.
What fuels my anger is how you treat your women. I'm angry that the number of rapes in "Islamic" countries keep going up. I'm angry because eveyone thinks Islam oppresses women because of misogynist people. I'm angry because some "scholars" claim that marital rape does not exist. I'm angry how you murder your sister,wife,cousin for petty reasons and then have the audacity to call it "honor killing".I'm angry because you think that you have some sort of claim on a women's life. I'm angry because your negative comments can drive young girls and boys to engage in unhealthy behaviors in order to change their body type to conform to the norms of society . I'm angry because you make me feel like I'm nothing. And most of all I'm angry at how powerless I'm to stop all of this. .
Take responsibility for your actions. Certainly Allah is the most just.
.

text:
The internalised misogynist inside of myself (I effing hate her) tells me that women shouldn't do 'certain things' because of the sexist narrative our society has laid out for us. It is through years of re-training that I have minimised the power she has over my thoughts...judging other women is just a quick way to get out of dealing with the things we dislike about OURSELVES. We seek comfort in other women's perceived 'flaws' in an attempt to avoid addressing our own insecurities
â€¢ 
Every time you catch yourself critiquing a woman on the choices that she makes, who she sleeps with, how she dresses...sit in it. Reflect. What is it about her that makes you feel so uncomfortable? Maybe she reminds you of yourself. The parts of yourself that you are ashamed of. Perhaps who you used to be? Or, maybe she's the very person you WANT to be? Making bold choices for herself that you are too afraid to? The choices that society has made you feel shameful of, because they go against the patriarchal narrative? Or maybe you just really fancy her and need to admit that ur queer and go ask her out?!
â€¢
Ask yourself WHY you think this way. Reprogram your patriarchal brainwashing. The girl you're jealous and hateful of isn't a bitch, your internalised misogynist is. Give it a name. Tell it to eff off! It's ruining your relationship with other women

Reposted from @florencegiven

text:
*Primitive prejudice misogynist
Dear Tamil movie industry*

Recently I watched Neerkonda Parvai, a tamil film directed by H.Vinoth. 
It was a Tamil remake of a Hindi film back in 2016. 
Disclaimer: This post contains spoilers regarding the movie; choice is in your hands. 
I am pretty impressed how this Tamil movie portrayed prejudice and discrimination towards women and male patriarchy. 
The story revolves around three young women persuaded by three guys to have dinner and drinks with them at a resort. One of these mischievous guys forced himself onto one of the girls and she resisted and refused to do anything sexual with him. He did not stopped so she instinctively grabbed a glass bottle beside her and smashed it into his head. The women escaped and his friends rushed him to the hospital. 
After a few days, the guys decided to threaten the girls by frightening their landlord to chase them out of the house, spreading edited explicit picture of one of the girls, stalking them and they even kidnapped one of the girls and molested her in the car. 
The situation escalated and they ended up in court. These three guys (from a high class and reputable background) decided to use whatever they can in their power to change the story. They stated that the girls requested them into having sexual contact with them in exchange for money and when the guys refused, one of the girls smashed the bottle onto his head. 
The story continues in court to show how these misogynistic men and their lawyer indirectly stated stereotypical and discriminative statements; -If a woman comes home late, she deserved whatever that happens to her at night -If a woman is unable to meet her financial requirements, she most likely resorted to prostitution. -If a woman talks and touches a guy in friendly manner, she is interested and even inviting him to have sex. *Continuation in comment section* 
Artwork: @maanushrinair

I feel the Tamil film industry should direct more movies as such and touch more on social issues such as rights, inequality, discrimination etc. This is because the Tamil film industry has a big impact on the public and instead of portraying typical things such as violence and romance, how about educating people on how to agree to disagree and how to come out of their comfort zone to consider opinions of others. 
On a side note, having one of the lead Indian actors Ajith acting in this movie certainly prevent any resentment to the ideology of the movie because famous actors are treated like Kings and Queens in India. 
I certainly do wonder what is to happen if someone not famous were to act in Ajithâ€™s place? 
All in all, Kudos to the director H.Vinoth and his crew! Her father died last year due to a cardiac attack.

My friend @vally.climbs tagged me this post that shook me to my core. A brief background is a man posted a picture posing â€œlike a girl.â€ This sentence angers me. Angers me to the point where I have no words. Today, however, I found those words.

Girls. Females. Vagina owners. Trans gender. Non-binary. You. Are. Enough. You are MORE than enough. Misogynistic humans have no right or power of opinion over YOU. Just because you are a GIRL, FEMALE, HUMAN WITH A VAGINA, TRANS GENDER, NON BINARY, does NOT lower your worth. 
Iâ€™m so sick of living in a world that, based on your sex, you are less valued. I hate that items that can be owned often have the female value placed on it. Cars? Often referred to as a female (â€œhere she isâ€ in reference to the car). I hate that women are often paid less than a man. I hate that women are expected to change their last name when married. I hate that women are expected to stay home with kids with (often) NO expectation for the father to be the stay at home parent. I hate that there are laws placed over womenâ€™s decisions with their bodies and NO laws placed over the man and his ejaculation. .

YOU- YES YOU, THE WOMAN READING THIS- YOU ARE VALUED.  YOU are important. YOU can change the world. YOU LIVE YOUR LIFE HOW YOU BEST KNOW AND WANT TO. Pose for pictures how you want, you hike when/how/what you want. Break out of the boundaries pushed upon you. And go friken hike like a human. Hike like a person. Hike proudly. Explore proudly. Raise people up. Be good, do good. Hike like a girl. #hikelikeagirl .

Thank you 
@tandemtrekking for bringing light and creating a community as we re-write what it means to #hikelikeagirl .

text:
Let me borrow the words of #Christ to begin the shaking of a table I have tagged â€œAfrican sexism in historical contextâ€

In todayâ€™s world many have learnt to jump on #bandwagons without critical and historical thinking! The high level of #mentalslavery has blinded us from deep appreciation of our truest self

If you ask 10 #Africans about their views on sexism/feminism in Africa - 7 in 10 will argue it is a highly #misogynist society - where womenâ€™s rights are subdued

Would I say they are right? Absolutely yes! In present day #Africa , due to the popularity of literary & elitist male chauvinists - we have three types of sexism - #Malignantsexism a view that â€œthereâ€™s hardly any good in a woman & #benignsexism which says by nature women are inferior to men

The third is #benevolentsexism (which I would confess I easily fell prey to) this is the view that because women are inferior (however subtly this is believed) they need special care & attention

However in the beginning it was not so! No I donâ€™t mean the #bible beginning, I mean in African #mythology & #history it was not so

text:
â€¢JUST A COFFEE THOUGHTâ€¢
I have 15 minutes to kill while waiting for the tram to head home and decide to splurge on an ice blended coffee. I've scratched out 3 poems which had beginnings but no endings. This style of narrating is called "stream of consciousness"; writing down your thoughts as they are flowing through your mind. Wait, a small chunk of chocolate is stuck in my straw. There, done. I have 12 more minutes to go.

There was a man in the tram on my way to town who was talking very loudly on the phone. He repeatedly said, "She's just a woman, asshole! You left bruises on her and I have to shut her up. Leave her alone with me tomorrow, I'll handle it." He then wiped the beads of sweat on his eyebrows. [scratched out profanities which followed - you can see it on the photo above]

I was baffled, truly. No, you are the butt hole. Nobody is just a woman or just a man. 
I gave him a disgusted look but the smug on his face stayed. My stop came and I had to leave. Tomorrow, I will think about that woman who was just a woman to him. I hope she won't just let it slide. She should just kick him between his legs and just leave her mark in his memories. For the rest of his life he should just remember; he is just an asshole and she is just a woman. 3 minutes to go - I have to leave the cafe.

text:
Greenpeace activists.

I have worked in a large gallery for ten years. I never say which because we are not supposed to talk about stuff that goes on. However, Iâ€™ve got something good-ish to say (for once) about whoever makes the rules there.

I donâ€™t think Iâ€™m giving too much away if I say my employer receives money from BP, since a lot of museums do. And so â€˜weâ€™ get protesters.

The gallery stance is to spot activists before they get in, and keep them out. Easier said than done, with budgets lower than ever. Most of my colleagues privately have total sympathy with Greenpeace. Not sure about the top brass, mind. 
I have seen many protesters and they have ALL been polite, quiet, non-violent and have left absolutely no mess behind.
We are told never to touch them and to calmly let them get on with their peaceful protest, which is over before you know it, and to make sure the public (who are never in any danger) come to no harm. 
Grabbing a protester, the way Mark Field did, is totally unprofessional.

The above picture is uncredited and taken from this weekendâ€™s i. It shows him grabbing Lucia Hunt. You can read the full article in one of my posts from a week ago, as I stitched Ms Hunt to my â€˜thingâ€™ as the â€˜face of the dayâ€™ on account of this â€˜kissâ€™. Itâ€™s the post where the first image is Gove and Stewart, but if you scroll along, you can see this other unprofessional incident. And also about how the Foreign Secretary referred to his partner as Japanese, when she is actually Chinese.

Happy Sunday.

text:
HIKE LIKE A GIRL.

My friend @vally.climbs tagged me this post that shook me to my core. A brief background is a man posted a picture posing â€œlike a girl.â€ This sentence angers me. Angers me to the point where I have no words. Today, however, I found those words.

Girls. Females. Vagina owners. Trans gender. Non-binary. You. Are. Enough. You are MORE than enough. Misogynistic humans have no right or power of opinion over YOU. Just because you are a GIRL, FEMALE, HUMAN WITH A VAGINA, TRANS GENDER, NON BINARY, does NOT lower your worth. 
Iâ€™m so sick of living in a world that, based on your sex, you are less valued. I hate that items that can be owned often have the female value placed on it. Cars? Often referred to as a female (â€œhere she isâ€ in reference to the car). I hate that women are often paid less than a man. I hate that women are expected to change their last name when married. I hate that women are expected to stay home with kids with (often) NO expectation for the father to be the stay at home parent. I hate that there are laws placed over womenâ€™s decisions with their bodies and NO laws placed over the man and his ejaculation. .

YOU- YES YOU, THE WOMAN READING THIS- YOU ARE VALUED.  YOU are important. YOU can change the world. YOU LIVE YOUR LIFE HOW YOU BEST KNOW AND WANT TO. Pose for pictures how you want, you hike when/how/what you want. Break out of the boundaries pushed upon you. And go friken hike like a human. Hike like a person. Hike proudly. Explore proudly. Raise people up. Be good, do good. Hike like a girl. #hikelikeagirl .

Thank you 
@tandemtrekking for bringing light and creating a community as we re-write what it means to #hikelikeagirl .

text:
â€¢JUST A COFFEE THOUGHTâ€¢
I have 15 minutes to kill while waiting for the tram to head home and decide to splurge on an ice blended coffee. I've scratched out 3 poems which had beginnings but no endings. This style of narrating is called "stream of consciousness"; writing down your thoughts as they are flowing through your mind. Wait, a small chunk of chocolate is stuck in my straw. There, done. I have 12 more minutes to go.

There was a man in the tram on my way to town who was talking very loudly on the phone. He repeatedly said, "She's just a woman, asshole! You left bruises on her and I have to shut her up. Leave her alone with me tomorrow, I'll handle it." He then wiped the beads of sweat on his eyebrows. [scratched out profanities which followed - you can see it on the photo above]

I was baffled, truly. No, you are the butt hole. Nobody is just a woman or just a man. 
I gave him a disgusted look but the smug on his face stayed. My stop came and I had to leave. Tomorrow, I will think about that woman who was just a woman to him. I hope she won't just let it slide. She should just kick him between his legs and just leave her mark in his memories. For the rest of his life he should just remember; he is just an asshole and she is just a woman. 3 minutes to go - I have to leave the cafe.

Greenpeace activists.

I have worked in a large gallery for ten years. I never say which because we are not supposed to talk about stuff that goes on. However, Iâ€™ve got something good-ish to say (for once) about whoever makes the rules there.

I donâ€™t think Iâ€™m giving too much away if I say my employer receives money from BP, since a lot of museums do. And so â€˜weâ€™ get protesters.

The gallery stance is to spot activists before they get in, and keep them out. Easier said than done, with budgets lower than ever. Most of my colleagues privately have total sympathy with Greenpeace. Not sure about the top brass, mind. 
I have seen many protesters and they have ALL been polite, quiet, non-violent and have left absolutely no mess behind.
We are told never to touch them and to calmly let them get on with their peaceful protest, which is over before you know it, and to make sure the public (who are never in any danger) come to no harm. 
Grabbing a protester, the way Mark Field did, is totally unprofessional.

The above picture is uncredited and taken from this weekendâ€™s i. It shows him grabbing Lucia Hunt. You can read the full article in one of my posts from a week ago, as I stitched Ms Hunt to my â€˜thingâ€™ as the â€˜face of the dayâ€™ on account of this â€˜kissâ€™. Itâ€™s the post where the first image is Gove and Stewart, but if you scroll along, you can see this other unprofessional incident. And also about how the Foreign Secretary referred to his partner as Japanese, when she is actually Chinese.

Happy Sunday.

text:
The character Kabir Singh, is basically an updated Devdas. The entire arc of the film is to somehow make his negativity attractive, explain it away as â€œunconventionalâ€ and have him find redemption despite his unforgivable ways. This remake is an unapologetic celebration of toxic masculinity.
Having watched and balked at Arjun Reddy for its celebration of a misogynistic, infantile bully of a hero, Kabir Singh felt like a doubly suffocating experience. One that makes you feel violated. Devdas at least had the headstrong Paro and graceful Chandramukhi, two beholden women alright but with personalities of their own, to bring some sense of balance to the man-woman game.  Here the woman is denied any agency whatsoever. Kiara Advani, who is a treat to watch on screen was actually not given more than 10 dialogues in the movie. She is a property, marked and owned by the man, who meekly follows him with eyes always down and is masochistic in allowing herself to bear with his violent ways. But later she falls in love with him, despite everything, because apparently heâ€™s her protector and saviour.
The entire film, is dependent on and propelled by the performance of the star at the centre. And however good Shahid Kapoor might be in living the trauma and angst of the character, you still canâ€™t get away from the sickening male entitlement. 
What does the filmmaker think women are meant for? Be sacrificial goats at the male altar? What fuels such proprietary behaviour in some men? What makes them think any woman they desire must return the sentiment? You keep waiting for the film to answer these questions, but they never come. Because this is not that kind of film. In fact as per the filmmakers â€“ ITS INTENSE LOVE.
Kabir Singh is an unmistakably misogynistic film, but the sad part is that itâ€™s exactly these troubling portions that the filmmakers peddle as intense love. If this is the great idea of man-woman dynamics, if this is a â€œhatkeâ€ love story, well just tell me another one. End of rant! - @cautiousdreamer_ 
Source : The Indian Express, New18,  The Hindu, India Today.

text:
Feeling like you hit a brick wall?

No matter what you try, you can't find peace: â€¢praying more
â€¢volunteering to teach another Sunday School class
â€¢submitting even more to your husband and pastor
â€¢homeschooling your kids
â€¢going on missions trips â€¢joining another ministry school

I understand because I have been there.

There is whole new existence available

that I have experienced

and I am never going back to the do-more life.

I live in a place of glorious self-worth in Jesus' identity.

Imagine God's seal of approval is yours 
even when you are failing.

When you know this, believe this glorious good news,

there is no longer any need to work yourself up into his favor.

The result is immediate--rest and peace with yourself and God.

You will crave time hearing his voice of reassurance.

You will know your requests are answered and you will move on to listening.

And what you hear is pure unconditional love and adoration

even when you are doing nothing.

You can't stay there long until you will be chomping at the bit to find out what his destiny is for you.

Surprise! You already knew deep down your whole life.

You just got too busy listening to the church's mandates, listening to man instead of your adoring creator.

You have been created with gifts and a personality that weave together to make up your life purpose.

Fun and adventure result from cooperating with God instead of submitting to church.

Being able to hear him gently remind you how he formed you is the beginning of a life filled with the satisfaction of knowing where you fit in the Kingdom.

I've never been happier, and it is my mission to write to help women who have been churchified understand their worth.

Interested in hearing more and getting exclusive behind-the-scenes email updates in addition to blog posts, subscribe to my blog. Link in bio.

â€œSlurs that you DID NOT reclaim, are not yours to use.â€ â£
â£
Plain and simple. Historically, groups of people who have been oppressed have been known to RECLAIM terms that have been used by oppressors towards them. Reclamation is the reappropriation of slurs, and this can be used as a form of empowerment to many. When outsiders continue to use these words, whether it be to dehumanize others, or to â€œreclaimâ€ it for themselves, it is insulting and disgraceful. Non-black people/Non-black POC using â€œniggaâ€, men using â€œbitchâ€, straight cis-gendered persons using LGBT slurs, etc.. Are examples of groups of people disregarding their social privileges and using terms that are not theirs to reclaim. Be mindful of the language you use and how it effects others. Respect otherâ€™s right to use terms that have been used against them, and check your privilege before you insert yourself into spaces that werenâ€™t created for you. â£

text:
#nowthispolitics - 
Meet the 25 white, #Republican men who decided to pass the strictest abortion ban in #Alabama ğŸ¤¨ You get this is a movement right? .
You know that Roe v. Wade will be next right? .
.

That decision of the U.S. Supreme Court in which the Court ruled that the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution provides a fundamental "right to privacy" that protects a pregnant woman's liberty to choose whether or not to have an abortion, while also ruling that this right is not absolute and must be balanced against the government's interests in protecting women's health and protecting prenatal life.
.
The Court resolved this balancing test by tying state regulation of abortion to the three trimesters of pregnancy: the Court ruled that during the first trimester, governments could not prohibit abortions; during the second trimester, abortions still could not be prohibited, but governments could "regulate the abortion procedure in ways that are reasonably related to maternal health"; during the third trimester, abortions could be prohibited entirely so long as the laws contained exceptions for cases when abortion was necessary to save the life of the mother. .
Because the Court classified the right to choose to have an abortion as "fundamental", the decision required courts to evaluate challenged abortion laws under the "strict scrutiny" standard, the highest level of judicial review in the United States.

#ReligiousAbuse: Abusers often find victims in religious circles. Reasons include teachings on forgiveness, shame surrounding divorce, And this part is important: Too many lessons on what a womanâ€™s role should be, & how they should act & behave compared to men.

Listed on the official abuse website: Roomtobesafe.org, a red flag in a relationship is â€œnoticing your partner has very traditional (or stereotypical) beliefs about gender roles.â€
.
Below is a quote taught to me by well-meaning Sunday school teachers & loved by many women I personally know. But guess what? I hate it. â€œThe world has enough women who are tough; we need women who are tender. There are enough women who are coarse; we need women who are kind. There are enough women who are rude; we need women who are refined. We have enough women of fame and fortune; we need more women of faith. We have enough greed; we need more goodness. We have enough vanity; we need more virtue. We have enough popularity; we need more purity.â€
.
My rewording: â€The world has enough women who donâ€™t realize you can be both tough and tender; we need more women to believe in their strength. We have enough women who feel they should put pleasing others before themselves, we need more women willing to speak their truth. There are enough women who feel they canâ€™t stand up for themselves because that would be rude and unrefined; we need more women who know they can take a stand and refuse to tolerate bad behavior. We donâ€™t have enough women of fame and fortune; we need more women (including women of faith) to not be ashamed of success or taking control of their finances. We have enough greed, we need more willing females to lead humanity. We have enough vanity; we need more women to stand up to those who believe women are only objects to be admired. We have enough popularity; we need more females driven by their true passions and supported for being authentic, rather than being judged while sitting in the pews.â€
.
